<h1>SHADERS</h1>
<p>// Every pixel — a parallel computation in the GPU's visual nervous system</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="divider"></div>
<section class="hidden" id="fragment">
<h2>// Fragment Shader Pipeline</h2>
<p>A fragment shader runs once for every pixel. It receives interpolated vertex attributes and outputs a final RGBA color. The entire visible universe of real-time graphics passes through this program, running millions of times per second in parallel on thousands of GPU cores.</p>
<div class="canvas-wrap">
<canvas height="240" id="fragCanvas"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-label">UV field visualization — move cursor</div>
</div>
<div class="slider-row"><label>// distortion</label><input id="distSlider" max="100" min="0" type="range" value="40"/><span id="distVal">0.40</span></div>
<div class="slider-row"><label>// color_shift</label><input id="colorShiftSlider" max="100" min="0" type="range" value="50"/><span id="colorShiftVal">0.50</span></div>
<div class="card-grid">
<div class="card"><h3>vUV / varyings</h3><p>Interpolated texture coordinates [0,1]² across the triangle surface. The primary navigation tool in fragment shader space.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>texture2D / texture</h3><p>Samples a texture at UV coordinates. Hardware bilinear filter, mipmap selection, and anisotropic filter all happen inside this single call.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>gl_FragColor</h3><p>Output vec4(r,g,b,a) in [0,1]. All the work of the shader converges to this one value written to the framebuffer.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>discard</h3><p>Kills the fragment entirely, making it transparent. Used for cutout materials without blending overhead.</p></div>
</div>
</section>
<div class="divider"></div>
<section class="hidden" id="playground">
<h2>// Shader Playground</h2>
<p>Live WebGL preview driven by GLSL fragment logic — every parameter change propagates to the GPU immediately. This is how Shadertoy, GLSL Sandbox, and TouchDesigner's GLSL TOP work.</p>
